ce:section.ce:para:
The morphologies of all C-dots were first characterized by transmission electron microscopy and atomic force microscopy. The typical TEM images of GT-C-dots, CT-C-dots, GD-C-dots and CD-C-dots are shown in Fig. 1
                     . All of the four C-dots have a quasi-spherical shape with diameters in the range of 2 nm–7 nm. The AFM images (Fig. 2
                     ) reveal that the heights of C-dots are in the similar range, further confirming the quasi-spherical shape of the prepared C-dots. High resolution TEM images illustrate crystallinity of the prepared C-dots, as shown in the inset of Fig. 1. The lattice parameters of GT-C-dots, CT-C-dots, GD-C-dots and CD-C-dots are ca. 0.24, 0.25, 0.21 and 0.25 nm, respectively, which are different to the intra-plane lattice parameter (0.214 nm) and inter-plane lattice parameter (0.340–0.403 nm) of the reported C-dots derived from carbon sources without nitrogen doping [43–45]. The mismatch of lattice parameters could be due to the presence of nitrogen and oxygen, which have also been observed in other nitrogen- or oxygen-rich C-dots [4,46]. The XRD patterns are shown in Fig. S1. For all of four samples, two broad peaks were found located at around 26° (002) and 45° (100), respectively. The size distributions of these four types of C-dots (Fig. 1E–H) indicate that both carbon sources (glucose and citric acid) and nitrogen sources (TTDDA and dopamine) contribute to the size of C-dots. The average sizes of C-dots derived from citric acid are obviously larger than those derived from glucose. This could be attributed to the fact that citric acid possesses carboxyl groups that can react with basic TTDDA or dopamine to form stable intermediates. Contrary to that, glucose that has only hydroxyls groups can only interact with TTDDA and dopamine through Van der Waals' forces such as hydrogen bonds. The weak interaction between glucose and TTDDA or dopamine causes the intermediates to easily slip into small fragments during the heat-treatment process, resulting in smaller C-dots. By using the same carbon source, the average size of C-dots derived from dopamine is somewhat larger than that derived from TTDDA, possibly due to dopamine containing phenyl ring.
